I. solution. The statement is not true. We prove this by a counterexample. Consider the following two sequences:

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
a_{n}=n^{2}, \text { if } n \text { is even, } & a_{n}=\frac{1}{n^{2}}, \text { if } n \text { is odd; } \\
b_{n}=\frac{1}{n^{2}}, \text { if } n \text { is even, } & b_{n}=n^{2}, \text { if } n \text { is odd. }
\end{array}
$$

The sequences $\left\{a_{n}\right\},\left\{b_{n}\right\}$ are clearly positive, and the series $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_{n}, \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} b_{n}$ are divergent, since

$$
\sum_{n=1}^{k} a_{n} \geq(k-1)^{2}, \quad \sum_{n=1}^{k} b_{n} \geq(k-1)^{2}
$$

for every positive integer $k$. On the other hand,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2 a_{n} b_{n}}{a_{n}+b_{n}}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2}{n^{2}+\frac{1}{n^{2}}}< \\
<2 \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n^{2}}<2\left(\sum_{n=2}^{\infty} \frac{1}{n(n-1)}+1\right)=2\left(\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\left(\frac{1}{n-1}-\frac{1}{n}\right)+1\right)=4
\end{gathered}
$$

Therefore, the series $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2 a_{n} b_{n}}{a_{n}+b_{n}}$ is positive and bounded, hence convergent.

II. solution. Let $\left\{c_{n}\right\}$ be a positive sequence such that $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} c_{n}$ is convergent. (For example, any geometric sequence with a ratio between 0 and 1.) Consider the following two sequences:

$$
a_{2 n}=1, a_{2 n-1}=c_{n} \text {, and } b_{2 n-1}=1, b_{2 n}=c_{n}
$$

for every natural number $n$. The sequences $\left\{a_{n}\right\}$ and $\left\{b_{n}\right\}$ are positive, and neither $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_{n}$ nor $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} b_{n}$ is convergent, since both sequences contain infinitely many ones. On the other hand, the terms of the series $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2 a_{n} b_{n}}{a_{n}+b_{n}}$ satisfy

$$
0<\frac{2 a_{2 n-1} b_{2 n-1}}{a_{2 n-1}+b_{2 n-1}}=\frac{2 a_{2 n} b_{2 n}}{a_{2 n}+b_{2 n}}=\frac{2 c_{n}}{c_{n}+1}<2 c_{n}
$$

therefore

$$
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2 a_{n} b_{n}}{a_{n}+b_{n}}=2 \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2 c_{n}}{c_{n}+1}<4 \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} c_{n}
$$

The series $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2 a_{n} b_{n}}{a_{n}+b_{n}}$ is a positive series bounded above by a convergent series, which implies the convergence of the series.

Remark. The statement of the problem can also be phrased as follows: if $\left\{a_{n}\right\}$ and $\left\{b_{n}\right\}$ are positive sequences and the series formed from the harmonic means of the corresponding terms $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2}{1 / a_{n}+1 / b_{n}}$ is convergent, then one of $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_{n}$ and $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} b_{n}$ is convergent. We have shown that this statement is not true. However, if the series formed from the arithmetic means of the corresponding terms $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left(a_{n}+b_{n}\right) / 2$ is convergent, then clearly $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_{n}$ and $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} b_{n}$ are bounded, hence convergent. Similarly, it can be shown that if $\left\{a_{n}\right\}$ and $\left\{b_{n}\right\}$ are positive and the series formed from the geometric means $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \sqrt{a_{n} b_{n}}$ is convergent, this does not imply the convergence of $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_{n}$ or $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} b_{n}$. To see this, it is enough to consider the sequences $\left\{a_{n}\right\}$ and $\left\{b_{n}\right\}$ defined by $a_{2 n}=b_{2 n-1}=1, a_{2 n-1}=b_{2 n}=c_{n}^{2}$ in the notation of the second solution.

